b25b6b77a0087ff8385941e5545d32ea: MathML+SVG in text/html doesn't seem like it'd be an exciting feature to many people - almost nobody even uses non-inline SVG, despite that being easy and useful and well supported b25b6b77a0087ff8385941e5545d32ea: Also I don't see why anyone would care about parsing rules, because they can just write proper valid pseudo-XHTML like they always have and it'll work fine in current browsers Things that are exciting to people here are probably almost completely separate from what is exciting to normal people :-) Most people don't write Google Maps Most people don't write sites of equivalent complexity to Google Maps I think I've encountered DOM uninteroperability far more than parsing uninteroperability b25b6b77a0087ff8385941e5545d32ea: "helps interoperability" seems too abstract a concept to get excited about - people will only care when it's solving the real problems they encounter, which are much more likely to be CSS and DOM problems hopes browsers could detect when they are running on a desktop PC, and therefore are unlikely to be moved, so if they don't have a GPS receiver then they could simply ask the user to enter their address once and then they will be able to implement the Geolocation API (and for laptops they could just ask for the address of each wireless access point you connect to) f139aba52f9fa1394b4034a7954b2220: That sounds like something that would need added OS and driver support (and hardware support too?), so it's unlikely to happen any time soon except on mobile devices

Huh?  You make DOM objects without a new already. document.createElement("foo"); ...why? ...why? ...what? (I am actually quite confused here, not being facetious.) New languages arent' javascript, and don't have the mixing of functions and classes and constructors. a11aabeeceeae6b8cb5d12ea06b56554: And even in the Classes proposal that tc39 accepted at the last meeting, you still new them up as normal.  (It's just syntax sugar for the existing prototype stuff.) Anyway, 'new' does something very specific - it sets "this" to a clone of the prototype.  Just calling the function doesn't do that; "this" is set as normal. You can make new-less calls still construct, but you ahve to do it manually. That's nice.  It's weird, and not idiomatic javascript to do so.  Outside of the oddness of some DOM constructors, it's not common for new-less constructors to work. Yeah, some of it. It's not that it's unpopular.  It's that there's no *reason* for it.  "new" has a purpose, and omitting it means the dev has to do more work.  It also makes the code less clear, imo, because you can no longer tell apart object construction from function calls. It's not semantic.  There is a functional difference.  I explained it.  Without "new", the dev has to do additional work in their function to clone the prototype themselves. ...yes, in js.  Because that's how "this" works.  If you're programming in a different language with different semantics for "this", or some other concept altogether (like real classes with dedicated constructor functions), then the situation is obviously different. It's funny when clueless people try to work up a righteous indignation. He was around earlier today. The worse API being "the DOM"? Yus. Yes.

Hi! One question: is there, by any means, anywhere, a definition, if in HTML (concrete: HTML 4.01) and/or it's parent, SGML, it's allowed and valid to shorten an entity (like &amp;) to "&;" (Ampersant + Semikolon) in a given <a href="URL with &; instead of &amp;"> construct, so that the W3C Markup Validator is right, in NOT labeling it as an error and let passing it as valid? Meaning: is it by any means correct and valid, to use "&;" instead of masking a "& with "&amp;" in a given URL? When NOT valid, why does the W3C Markup Validator say so, while parsing/validating against HTML 4.01 strict  -- and in contrast (and my expectation) throws an (from my point of view expectable and correct) error, when parsing/validating against XHTML 1.0 Strict while sticking to the Mimetype text/html)? Thanks. P.S: Or might there be an error by the W3C Markup Validator in doing so and should be fixed? 8d5c0dd1af8dbfd69120fd4882cb3a68: That's, what I wonder about. I've been of that opinion until today, too. Until I pasted a HTML 4 code fragment into the Validator's interface today and tried to validate it. A code fragment like that: <a href="http://maps.google.de/maps?f=q&amp;source=s_q&amp;hl=en&amp;geocode=&amp;...">BB</a>. The former it has been (via copy & paste): <a href="http://maps.google.de/maps?f=q&source=s_q&hl=en&geocode=&...">. That throws indeed an error. But when you ch the "&" into "&;" , so that it's <a href="http://maps.google.de/maps?f=q&;source=s_q&;hl=en&;geocode=&;...">, the validator throws no error and says, it's valid. And only, when validating against HTML 4.01 Strict. Overwriting it with a XHTML 1.0 Strict doctype by the validator's gui interface, the following (correct) error (or at least warning) occurs: Warning Line xx, Column yy: 'character "&" is the first character of a delimiter but occurred as data'... who and what is right and valid? Is it possible to see "&;" as a a valid form of an (SGML or HTML or XML) Entity instead of masking it and writing a correct &amp;? 8d5c0dd1af8dbfd69120fd4882cb3a68: Yes, I think so, too. And until today, I also thought about it either concerning SGML and HTML... 8d5c0dd1af8dbfd69120fd4882cb3a68: Thanks for pointing me to this particular chapter of the spec. That's a good help. May it be, that The markup validator has got a bug there and should instead throw an error, at least a warning, than parsing it commendless and saying, it's valid HTML 4.01 Strict? 8d5c0dd1af8dbfd69120fd4882cb3a68: what seems right for you? That there is possible an error of the validator's parser, or that it's OK, and there is no error with the validator's parser? 8d5c0dd1af8dbfd69120fd4882cb3a68: OK. 8d5c0dd1af8dbfd69120fd4882cb3a68: I've sent a PM to Ville Skytt?§ (who is one of the core maintainers of the validator) some minutes ago. Before asking on the mailing list, I ask him personally. 8d5c0dd1af8dbfd69120fd4882cb3a68: HTML5 parser: yes, that's what I expect in all cases, also in HTML 4. Validating against XHTML 1.0 this throws such an error, too. But against HTML4: no error, valid. 8d5c0dd1af8dbfd69120fd4882cb3a68: Thanks so far.

&amp; cannot be shorten to &; now I don't think &; should be saccepted as valid either s/sac/ac/ XML is clear that &; isn't allowed see http://www.w3.org/TR/REC-xml/#NT-EntityRef for SGML, I'd be surprised if this was valid as well, but I can't check that fact right now that seems right to me. you might want to report that back to the validator mailing list error of the validator's parser the html5 validator reports an error btw Error: & did not start a character reference. (& probably should have been escaped as &amp;.) www.w3.org/sdfgfd&;dfgs

Then <noscript> isn't allowed and will have no effect, and the meta refresh will be processed as normal http://whatwg.org/html5#the-noscript-element - "Note: The noscript element is only effective in the HTML syntax, it has no effect in the XHTML syntax." (because it's implemented by changing the way the element is parsed, which is impossible in XHTML) is talking about HTML5 since that's most likely to reflect reality, and doesn't know what older specs might say If you brush enough things under your carpet to create a giant pile then it looks quite like your carpet is magically flying It is quite a recommended strategy a924fb58d2c25874322f4e5126f608b9: Declare the elephant to be Somebody Else's Problem and then you won't have to worry about it Its examples don't even use xmlns on <html> If you care what browsers should do and what desktop browsers probably do do, then you should refer to HTML5; if you care what weird mobile browsers do, you should test them directly XHTML-MP seems to be vague enough that it's either useless or wrong or both ("All sections and appendixes, except "Scope" and "Error! Not a valid bookmark self-reference.", are normative" - interesting section name) Seems sensible to me to consistently stick with what HTML5 defines, except in cases where compatibility with existing content requires different behaviour As far as I can see, the only noscript behaviour that HTML5 defines is in the HTML parser (which switches to RAWTEXT parsing mode if scripting is enabled, so the content will be treated as text and not as markup) (and the HTML parser is not used for XHTML pages) and otherwise it's treated exactly the same as a <foobar> element a924fb58d2c25874322f4e5126f608b9: You could just say "like a <span>" :-) (If compatibility with existing content requires different behaviour, then HTML5 should be updated, unless it's an obscure mode-specific thing for mobile browsers or whatever and has to be incompatible with normal web page behaviour) had forgotten about rendering HTML5 says "The user agent is expected to hide noscript elements for whom scripting is enabled, irrespective of CSS rules." so probably it should be non-rendered in both HTML and XHTML Does WebKit attempt or claim to support XHTML-MP? rather than just supporting a single "XHTML" (which is likely to be closest to the XML serialization of HTML5)

parsing rules written. next is... the processing model, i guess so moving an application around on a host breaks it? i guess we could really? fair enough the problem i see though is that i think duplicate installs of the same software on a host are going to be at least as likely as moving installed software around on a host so you're just trading conflicts for breakages (and in both cases the software can be written/configured to work around it) but it's only gonna be an issue when you install the same software, and software can already just use location.path as part of their database name if they want it requires one application software author to make the effort, instead of every user moving apps around s/apps/that app/ my point is i don't really see it as being much of a gain in either direction there are tradeoffs and i don't really see either as being better than the other (except that the status quo is simpler to spec and implement)

Hi Zerq :) Indeed. Well, actually, I'm quite sick, so maybe only 50 50%, rather As for your idea‚Ä¶ There are two parts. One is inconsistant date formats, which is a problem when moving between the USA and European date formats all the time. Year-Month-Day is unambiguous and sites that demand age verification could be clearer if they used that. Of course, the other version is to switch the month into named form, rather than numeral In terms of microformats, there are then two parts. Yep 1. If the site has taken an OpenID/URL-based login already, then there could be an hCard read at the other end with a published birth month/year. 2. The site could use a stanard set of classnames for the day/month/year form fields, and browsers existing auto-complete funtionality could be enhanced to respond to them In microformats as they stand, we don't have granular classnames for dates, though. Yes, that's true <input type=date> That's outside the scope of microformats. c74f596e4fe95fc3bb8726dbde2031b0 The problem with <input type=date> is taht the fallback is to a standard text field. Which is fantastic, in a technical progressive enhancement way. But, I suspect, the user experience of entering a full date in a single field, will cause errors. Sites use separate input fields for day/month/year for a reason Now, when browser support for type=date is large enough, sure, there will be a switch, but it won't be as super-soon as with other aspects of HTML5 Heh. Let's keep focused on the microformats please, ae2616b2b7f8bd9e7d2d5c567a80e5a2 :)

Is html5test.com actually a competent testing service? Some of the tests look bogus to me. Like testing for specific audio and video codecs. And it reports that Chrome dev channel doesn't support the autocomplete attribute, which is nonsense -- browsers have all supported that for years, haven't they? doesn't trust it Safari and Chrome have practically identical HTML5 conformance if you compare comparable versions, because they both use WebKit. Not ones that are relevant to almost any of the features that html5test.com supposedly test. A few, yes, but not many.

We do different things on top of that base, though. Some things show up in Chrome before we push them all the way back to Webkit, frex. And presumably the same sometimes happens with Safari. Yeah, wouldn't know about that. That makes sense.  Random users have no idea how to evaluate the quality of tests or their coverage. They *can* evaluate whether or not it runs, and how pretty a results page is.

It seems the popularity of a test suite is very highly correlated with how easy it is for a random user to run it in their own browser and see a big clear interestingly-designed page indicating the results and very loosely correlated with the quality or range of its test cases (Popularity isn't a particularly important metric for a test suite, though) 1e10d84b3917ae58049be95b0071cf7f: Those principles were mostly just writing down the principles that had been used in the WHATWG process so there's no difference (They weren't written down explicitly before then) (mostly since they were already obvious to most WHATWG members)

hi 73eaf221abca1b8244e34b0b9e76ac46 73eaf221abca1b8244e34b0b9e76ac46: is it worth it? what's the core issue? no, we just look at the first but also, we expose an object attribute called xml-roles which is just the role attribute exactly reproduced char for char i realize that doesn't help much though i'm sure we could do better with multiple roles, but no one is doing that yet in fact no one is really using roles as landmarks at all, even the obvious ones like main and navigation i guess, we have worse issues that i see as more important -- like harmonizing tree grid across platforms, handling the owns property better, caching relations (which i guess opera already does), and a few other things 73eaf221abca1b8244e34b0b9e76ac46: but if you decide it's worth putting into the proposal, i should be able to do it for ff3 73eaf221abca1b8244e34b0b9e76ac46: i'm wrong, we only allow one role in ff2 i'll reply ah, so are you going to start putting a11y API details in there? i think it's a good idea to do that, but, not all a11y apis are the same there are tradeoffs in the past w3c splits that off into a techniques doc which just leads to a too-abstract spec imo on the other hand web authors might be confused and there are differences between atk/at-spi, Iaccessible2, Universal Access, UI Automation, etc. but i'm glad to help b8810fee2f4a71f849f3f7409546d1d9: it is microsoft's new API for vista what happened is they gave up on msaa which was a problem, because people had lots of msaa code in apps and assistive tech and UIA was just an API for  managed code so IBM worked with the community to build IAccessible2, which are API extensions to MSAA and matches closely with ATK/AT-SPI on Linux I was part of that effort it's what we're using in FIrefox now because it can build on msaa support and yet is very similar to ATK, you can leverage a lot of existing code and get cross platform a11y the AT vendors had a lot less work to implement support for it, because they get to build on top of exisiting support for MSAA 73eaf221abca1b8244e34b0b9e76ac46: http://developer.mozilla.org/en/docs/ARIA_to_API_mapping b8810fee2f4a71f849f3f7409546d1d9: universal access is cool because it just name value pairs. It's loosely spec'd which honestly is an advantage in this space, because you don't have to rev a whole lot of binary software in lock step to get new features in you can just expose some new a11y property and then ask ATs to support that But with binary APIs, adding new features is a total nightmare b8810fee2f4a71f849f3f7409546d1d9: and the values in the name value pairs don't have to be strings, it can be a hash table for example so you can send any event data you want, for example, it's great the big disadvantage is that there is really only one (closed) screen reader supporting it, which is owned by the platform vendors so it is harder to influence them if you need new features, like accessible live regions or drag and drop, or whatever but, to answer your question, the name/value pairs Apple is using most likely fit well enough, but we only have stub support for UA in Mozilla so I can't say what the major integration issues will be yet b8810fee2f4a71f849f3f7409546d1d9: right, and you can find out by looking at other apps that apple has written, or looking at their docs but docs are always wrong or out of date for anything like this never gets all the details my big concern with spending a lot of resources on UA support in Mozilla is, how will we get Apple to change Voice Over when we need it, when obviously Safari is more important to them. I see a conflict of interest, but they aren't interested in open sourcing it So we might let Opera take the lead on that one :) b8810fee2f4a71f849f3f7409546d1d9: hwaara needed a real job instead of grants so he has stopped working on it we have a good start, though b8810fee2f4a71f849f3f7409546d1d9: i think it's ok, one step at a time we're doing a ton but to be honest, if i had resources i'd consider putting them into ARIA support in WebKit first, because then we can influence Voice Over first once everything works well there, we'll know exactly what support in Mozilla should look like since my goal is a11y for the whole web 73eaf221abca1b8244e34b0b9e76ac46: not a problem do pick out the aria role either first aria role whatever you decide first role is obviously easiest 73eaf221abca1b8244e34b0b9e76ac46: don't forget the xhtml role module roles have no prefix so that rule wouldn't work for role="navigation menu" 73eaf221abca1b8244e34b0b9e76ac46: i have an array of wai-aria roles in alphabetical order. i think the most performant rule to implement might actually be:    1) get the role attribute, 2) for each aria role in alphabetical order, check to see if it is in the the role attribute that way you only have to iterate once but it's kind of a lame rule that's fine what b8810fee2f4a71f849f3f7409546d1d9 said, but i don't think we need to spec the binary search of course just spec that we use the first aria role 73eaf221abca1b8244e34b0b9e76ac46: but, role="presentation" must be alone or it is ignored because it's inconsistent to say it's presentation + something else we check that separately in an earlier stage it would be fastest just to look for that in the string

is back 15bc6e4578edf59ea5e901ffb83c59dd: i think there are several reasons for using elements rather than attributes for article &c 15bc6e4578edf59ea5e901ffb83c59dd: (1) it's easier to author and maintain markup with element names instead of lots of divs 15bc6e4578edf59ea5e901ffb83c59dd: (2) if we continue reusing div for anything new this way we would end up with DivML 1.0 or something after a while 15bc6e4578edf59ea5e901ffb83c59dd: (3) it prevents the case where an element is both an article and nav at the same time, or where the attribute is placed on bogus places 15bc6e4578edf59ea5e901ffb83c59dd: (4) it's more performant to process elements than attributes in the general case (look at the headings and sections section for how article is part of the document outline algorithm) (2) i don't think it breaks anything (the content is still accessible as if the tags weren't there, no different from say <label>), it just isn't possible to style in some browsers why is it better to use attributes instead of elements? as i said, it would complicate processing, so i don't think using attributes would make the language simpler in any way one workaround is to use xhtml5 :) another might be to fix up the dom with script afterwards they can apply to multiple elements yeah it could be argued that we should combine all sectioning elements (except body) to just <section> and then use an attribute for what kind of section but i'm not sure what the advantage would be indeed... i think this needs to be pointed out very explicitly in the spec... in a nutshell div doesn't affect the document outline section is not intended to be a catch-all replacement of div but i fear many authors will go "oh, section is the new div, i should replace all my divs with sections!" q.v. b->strong sure here's an experiment: http://simon.html5.org/sandbox/html/w3c-home-in-html5 there isn't much that can be used today in practice :) :) 15bc6e4578edf59ea5e901ffb83c59dd: probably to not upset the semanticists or so that will make em and strong be the de facto italics and bold elements but they already are see http://lists.whatwg.org/pipermail/whatwg-whatwg.org/2007-January/009060.html indeed trying to force authors to use semantic markup doesn't work, they will instead misuse semantic elements for presentational purposes additionally, semantics is not an end of itself, it's more a means to achieve device independence we already have 4. why forbid one pair of them? Because they have different meanings. Yes. To something that makes more sense. In written Norwegian, titles of books, magazines, newspapers, movies, records, TV programs and plays are to be displayed in italics. Those italics are not emphasis. And they are not really presentational. When we have an element that does the job (<i>), there is no point in requring the author to use <span class='title-of-book'> or some other nonsense. 15bc6e4578edf59ea5e901ffb83c59dd: Exactly. Which is what the HTML5 spec says. <i> is used to markup ‚Äúa span of text in an alternate voice or mood, or otherwise offset from the normal prose, such as a taxonomic designation, a technical term, an idiomatic phrase from another language, a thought, a ship name, or some other prose whose typical typographic presentation is italicized‚Äù. No. I would write ‚Äú<i>Menneskehetens rikdommer</i> av Leo Huberman er en bra bok.‚Äù It might not be neccessary. But it is very useful. Especially <article> and <section>. Standardization. I can tell my web browser to don't bother printing <header>s, <footer>s or <nav>s, because they are not useful on paper. That is also possible, I guess. But standardization of commonly used classes of elements is useful anyway. Both for page authors and browser vendors. Standardization makes it easier to write and parse documents. Sure. But why _not_ standardize the most commonly used classes? footer is the most widespread class on the web. http://code.google.com/webstats/2005-12/classes.html
